* 1933: Welles's stage production of ''[[Twelfth Night (1933 film)|Twelfth Night]]'' for the [[Todd Seminary for Boys|Todd School for Boys]] received first prize<ref name="Welles TIOW" />{{Rp|330}} from the Chicago Drama League after competition at the [[Century of Progress]] Exposition of 1933, the Chicago World's Fair.<ref name="Drama League">{{cite news |title=Amateur Dramatic Groups to Compete for Trophy at Fair |newspaper=[[Ruston Daily Leader]] |publisher=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date= July 7, 1933}}</ref>{{efn|"Amateur dramatic groups from all sections of Metropolitan Chicago will compete this summer at Enchanted Island, World's Fair fairyland for children at [[A Century of Progress]], for a silver cup to be awarded by the Chicago Drama League, Miss Anna Agress, director of the Children's Theatre on the Island, has announced. Twenty-four groups, ranging from Thespians of years' experience to child actors, are on the schedule. Although most of the program will be played during July and August, the contest opened several days ago with the Todd School for Boys, of Woodstock, Ill., presenting Shakespeare's ''Twelfth Night''. The Todd boys were the 1932 cup winners."<ref name="Drama League" />}}
* 1938: As director of the [[Mercury Theatre]], Welles received the New York Drama Study Club Award for "the greatest contribution toward a living, breathing theatre this season".<ref>{{cite news |date=April 8, 1938 |title='Jitters' Opening Now Due on May 2 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F06E1DD1731E03ABC4053DFB2668383629EDE&legacy=true |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=August 29, 2017 |archive-date=August 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830063052/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F06E1DD1731E03ABC4053DFB2668383629EDE&legacy=true |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1939: For "his most conspicuous contribution this last year to the theatre and to radio drama," Welles received the [[Essex County, New Jersey|Essex County]] Symphony Society's first annual Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=April 8, 1938 |title=Award to Orson Welles: Stage and Radio Producer Is Honored by Jersey Group |url=http://www.mediafire.com/view/q16t3wqlmaqmwtr/.png |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=September 1, 2019 |archive-date=August 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803084700/http://www.mediafire.com/view/q16t3wqlmaqmwtr/.png |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1941: ''Citizen Kane'' received the [[1941 New York Film Critics Circle Awards|New York Film Critics Circle Award]] for Best Picture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyfcc.com/awards/?awardyear=1941 |title=1941 Awards |publisher=[[New York Film Critics Circle]] |access-date=February 17, 2016 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093319/http://www.nyfcc.com/awards/?awardyear=1941 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1942: The [[National Board of Review]] voted ''Citizen Kane'' Best Film of 1941,<ref>{{cite magazine |date=January 1942 |title=Ten Best 1941 |url=https://archive.org/stream/nationalboardofr1415nati#page/4/mode/1up |magazine=National Board of Review Magazine |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |volume=XVII |issue=1 |page=4 |access-date=February 17, 2016 }}</ref> and recognized Welles for his performance.<ref>{{cite magazine |date=January 1942 |title=Ten Best 1941 |url=https://archive.org/stream/nationalboardofr1415nati#page/6/mode/1up |magazine=National Board of Review Magazine |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |volume=XVII |issue=1 |page=6 |access-date=February 17, 2016 }}</ref>
* 1942: ''Citizen Kane'' received nine nominations at the [[14th Academy Awards|1941 Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] for Welles. It won the [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Original Screenplay)|Best Original Screenplay]], an award Welles shared with Herman J. Mankiewicz.<ref name="AA Database">{{cite web |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org |title=Academy Awards Database |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |access-date=August 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410083342/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>
* 1943: ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' was nominated for four [[15th Academy Awards|1942 Academy Awards]], including Best Picture.<ref name="AA Database" />
* 1945: On May 24, 1945, the Interracial Film and Radio Guild honored Welles for his contributions to interracial harmony through radio. Presented at the [[Shrine Auditorium]] in Los Angeles, the guild's second annual awards ceremony also honored [[Eddie "Rochester" Anderson]], [[Norman Corwin]], [[Bing Crosby]], [[Bette Davis]], [[Lena Horne]], [[James Wong Howe]], [[Earl Robinson]], Nathan Straus and Miguel C. Torres.<ref name="Whaley" />{{Rp|214–215}}<ref>"Straus Given Trophy". ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]'', June 4, 1945, page 24.</ref>
* 1947: ''[[The Stranger (1946 film)|The Stranger]]'' was nominated for the [[Golden Lion]] at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/en/awards.php?award_id=venice&year=1947|title=Venice Film Festival 1947 – FilmAffinity|website=FilmAffinity|language=en|access-date=April 18, 2018|archive-date=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418161158/https://www.filmaffinity.com/en/awards.php?award_id=venice&year=1947|url-status=live}}</ref>
* 1952: ''[[Othello (1951 film)|Othello]]'' won the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[1952 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/01/movies/film-welles-s-othello-made-chaos-into-an-art-form.html |title=Film; Welles's Othello Made Chaos into an Art Form |last=Yagoda |first=Ben |date=1992 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=April 8, 2018 |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809025423/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/01/movies/film-welles-s-othello-made-chaos-into-an-art-form.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1958: Although Universal Pictures did its best to prevent ''[[Touch of Evil]]'' from being selected for the 1958 Brussels World Film Festival—part of the [[Expo 58]] [[world's fair]]—the film received its European premiere and Welles was invited to attend. To his astonishment,<ref>{{cite book |last=Callow |first=Simon |date=2015 |title=Orson Welles: One-Man Band |location=New York |publisher=Viking |page=277 |isbn=978-0-670-02491-9 |author-link=Simon Callow }}</ref> Welles collected the two top awards. ''Touch of Evil'' received the [[International Federation of Film Critics|International Critics Prize]], and Welles was recognized for his body of work.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fipresci.org/festival-reports/1958/brussels-world-film-festival |title=1958 Brussels World Film Festival |publisher=[[International Federation of Film Critics]] (FIPRESCI) |access-date=May 15, 2018 |archive-date=May 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516014948/http://www.fipresci.org/festival-reports/1958/brussels-world-film-festival |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lyons |first=Leonard |date=July 10, 1958 |title=The Lyons Den   |work=The Salt Lake Tribune }}</ref>
* 1959: Welles received a special [[List of Peabody Award winners (1950–59)|1958]] [[Peabody Award]] for ''[[The Fountain of Youth (film)|The Fountain of Youth]]'',<ref name="Peabody">{{cite web |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/fountain-of-youth |title=Fountain of Youth |publisher=[[Peabody Awards]] |access-date=May 15, 2018 |archive-date=May 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516015442/http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/fountain-of-youth |url-status=live }}</ref> the only unsold TV pilot ever so honored.
* 1959: For their ensemble work in ''[[Compulsion (1959 film)|Compulsion]]'', Orson Welles, [[Bradford Dillman]] and [[Dean Stockwell]] shared the prize for Best Actor at the [[1959 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name="Welles TIOW" />{{Rp|425}}
* 1966: ''[[Chimes at Midnight]]'' was screened in competition for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the 1966 Cannes Films Festival and won the 20th Anniversary Prize ("Honneure") and the Technical Grand Prize. In Spain, it won the Citizens Writers Circle Award for Best Film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/19/movies/critic-s-notebook-chimes-at-midnight-welles-s-own-shakespeare.html |title=Critic's Notebook Chimes at Midnight Welles's Own Shakespeare |last=Canby |first=Vincent |date=1992 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=April 8, 2018 |archive-date=April 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409043323/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/19/movies/critic-s-notebook-chimes-at-midnight-welles-s-own-shakespeare.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1968: Welles was nominated for Best Foreign Actor in a Leading Role at the [[21st British Academy Film Awards]] for his performance in ''[[Chimes at Midnight]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awards.bafta.org/keyword-search?keywords=Chimes+at+Midnight/ |title=BAFTA Award Search |website=BAFTA.org |access-date=April 8, 2018 |archive-date=May 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515183707/http://awards.bafta.org/keyword-search?keywords=Chimes+at+Midnight%2F |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1970: The [[Venice Film Festival]] awarded Welles the [[Golden Lion]] for Career Achievement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/history/awards3.html?back=true|title=The awards of the Venice Film Festival|website=La Biennale di Venezia|access-date=January 1, 2017|archive-date=June 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607153233/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/history/awards3.html?back=true|url-status=live}}</ref>
* 1970: Welles was given an [[Academy Honorary Award]] for "superlative and distinguished service in the making of motion pictures."<ref name="movies">{{cite book|last=Verswijver|first=Leo |title="Movies Were Always Magical": Interviews with 19 Actors, Directors, and Producers from the Hollywood of the 1930s Through the 1950s|publisher=McFarland|year=2003|page=89|isbn=978-0-7864-1129-0}}</ref> Welles did not attend the ceremony: "I didn't go, because I feel like a damn fool at those things. I feel foolish, really foolish. ...&nbsp;I made a piece of film and said that I was in Spain, and thanked them."<ref name="Leaming" />{{Rp|511}}
* 1975: Welles received the [[AFI Life Achievement Award|American Film Institute Lifetime Achievement Award]].<ref>{{cite web| title=The AFI Life Achievement Awards| url=http://www.afi.com/laa/default.aspx| publisher=American Film Institute| access-date=April 28, 2017| archive-date=July 9, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709103222/http://www.afi.com/laa/default.aspx| url-status=live}}</ref>
* 1976: [[19th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word or Non-Musical Album]] for "Great American Documents", shared with [[Helen Hayes]], [[Henry Fonda]] and [[James Earl Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&field_nominee_work_value=Great+American+Documents&year=1976&genre=All |title=Great American Documents |publisher=GRAMMY Search Database |access-date=April 28, 2017 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304120147/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&field_nominee_work_value=Great+American+Documents&year=1976&genre=All |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1978: Welles was presented with the [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 1978|Los Angeles Film Critics Association Career Achievement Award]].<ref>{{cite web| title=4th Annual Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards| url=http://www.lafca.net/years/1978.html| publisher=Los Angeles Film Critics Association| access-date=April 28, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429010153/http://www.lafca.net/years/1978.html| archive-date=April 29, 2012| url-status=dead}}</ref>
* 1979: Welles received the [[21st Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Recording]] for the complete motion picture soundtrack for ''Citizen Kane''.<ref>{{cite document|title=''Citizen Kane''|publisher=WorldCat  |year=1978|oclc = 9006065}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Orson+Welles&field_nominee_work_value=&year=1978&genre=All |title=Citizen Kane |publisher=GRAMMY Search Database |access-date=January 1, 2017 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031729/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Orson+Welles&field_nominee_work_value=&year=1978&genre=All |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1979: Welles was inducted into the [[National Association of Broadcasters]] [[NAB Broadcasting Hall of Fame|Broadcasting Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nab.org/events/awards/pastAwardWinners.asp?id=1926 |title=Past Award Recipients |website=Broadcasting Hall of Fame |publisher=[[National Association of Broadcasters]] |access-date=April 28, 2017 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404044153/https://www.nab.org/events/awards/pastAwardWinners.asp?id=1926 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1981: Welles received a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Spoken Word Recording]] for his role on ''[[Donovan's Brain]]''.<ref>{{cite document|title=Donovan's Brain |publisher=WorldCat  |year=1980 |oclc = 8801102}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Orson+Welles&field_nominee_work_value=Donovan%27s+Brain&year=All&genre=All |title=Donovan's Brain |publisher=GRAMMY Search Database |access-date=January 1, 2017 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062130/http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Orson+Welles&field_nominee_work_value=Donovan's+Brain&year=All&genre=All |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1982: In Paris on February 23, 1982, President [[François Mitterrand]] presented Welles with the Order of Commander of the [[Légion d'honneur]], the highest civilian decoration in France.<ref name="Welles TIOW" />{{Rp|449|date=May 2012}}<ref name="McBride" />{{Rp|207|April 2014}}
* 1982: Welles was nominated for Best Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] for his role in ''[[Butterfly (1982 film)|Butterfly]]'', the same role that had him nominated for the [[3rd Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Award]] for Worst Supporting Actor, won by [[Ed McMahon]] in the same film, which also won the award for Worst Picture.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}
* 1983: Welles was made a member of the [[Académie des Beaux-Arts]].<ref name="Leaming" />{{Rp|508}}
* 1983: Welles was an inaugural recipient of the [[British Film Institute Fellowship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/about-bfi/senior-staff-governors-bfi-fellows/bfi-fellows |title=BFI Fellows |publisher=British Film Institute |access-date=September 15, 2018 |archive-date=September 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922062930/http://www.bfi.org.uk/about-bfi/senior-staff-governors-bfi-fellows/bfi-fellows |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1984: The [[Directors Guild of America]] presented Welles with its greatest honor, the [[Directors Guild of America Award|D. W. Griffith Award]].<ref name="NYT obit">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0506.html |title=Orson Welles is Dead at 70; Innovator of Film and Stage |publisher=[[The New York Times]], October 11, 1985 |access-date=May 15, 2014 |archive-date=November 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115112759/http://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0506.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1984: Welles received a Special Fellowship from [[The Academy of Magical Arts]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Larsen|first=Bill|date=November 1984|title=The Academy of Magical Arts 17th Annual Awards Banquet and Show|url=http://askalexander.org/display/37182/Genii/37|journal=Genii|volume=48|issue=11|pages=37|url-access=subscription|access-date=December 21, 2017|archive-date=December 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205164443/https://askalexander.org/unregistered?p=%2Fdisplay%2F37182%2FGenii%2F37|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame|url=http://www.magiccastle.com/hall_of_fame/|website=The Academy of Magical Arts|access-date=December 21, 2017|archive-date=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923215304/http://www.magiccastle.com/hall_of_fame/|url-status=live}}</ref>
* 1985: Welles received the Career Achievement Award from the [[National Board of Review]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/1985/ |title='1985 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |access-date=September 7, 2015 |archive-date=August 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820014742/http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/1985/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1988: Welles was inducted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiohof.org/orson_welles.htm |title=Orson Welles |publisher=[[National Radio Hall of Fame]] |access-date=April 28, 2017 |archive-date=July 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724101610/http://www.radiohof.org/orson_welles.htm |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 1993: The 1992 audiobook version of ''[[This is Orson Welles]]'' by Welles and Peter Bogdanovich was nominated for a [[35th Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] for Best Spoken Word or Non-Musical Album.<ref>"Rock to opera, a full list of nominees"; ''[[USA Today]]'', January 8, 1993</ref><ref>''This is Orson Welles'', HarperAudio (September 30, 1992) {{ISBN|1-55994-680-6}} (audiocassette)</ref>
* 1998: In [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies|1998]] and [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)|2007]], the [[American Film Institute]] ranked ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' as the greatest American movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.afi.com/orson-welles-citizen-kane-75th-anniversary/|title=15 Facts About Orson Welles' CITIZEN KANE|website=American Film|language=en-US|access-date=July 16, 2019|archive-date=July 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716153100/https://blog.afi.com/orson-welles-citizen-kane-75th-anniversary/|url-status=live}}</ref> These other Welles films were nominated for the AFI list: ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942, director/producer/screenwriter); ''[[The Third Man]]'' (1949, actor); ''[[Touch of Evil]]'' (1958, actor/director/screenwriter); and ''[[A Man for All Seasons (1966 film)|A Man for All Seasons]]'' (1966, actor).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmsite.org/afi400films.html|title=AFI's Greatest American Films – Nominees|website=www.filmsite.org|access-date=July 16, 2019|archive-date=July 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715064255/https://www.filmsite.org/afi400films.html|url-status=live}}</ref>
* 1999: The American Film Institute acknowledged Welles as one of the top 25 male motion picture stars of Classic Hollywood cinema in its survey, [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Stars]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/100Years/stars.aspx |title=AFI's 100 Years … 100 Stars |date=1999 |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |access-date=August 17, 2015 |archive-date=October 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025072655/http://www.afi.com/100Years/stars.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 2002: Welles was voted the greatest film director of all time in two [[British Film Institute]] polls, of directors<ref name="BFI Directors" /> and critics.<ref name="BFI Critics" />
* 2002: A highly divergent genus of Hawaiian spiders ''[[Orsonwelles]]'' was named in his honor.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Hormiga|first= Gustavo|year= 2002|title= ''Orsonwelles'', a new genus of giant linyphiid spiders (Araneae) from the Hawaiian Islands|journal= Invertebrate Systematics|volume= 16|issue= 3|pages= 369–448|url= http://www.gwu.edu/~spiders/content/publications/Hormiga%202002.pdf|doi= 10.1071/IT01026|access-date= September 24, 2014|archive-date= September 27, 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130927171242/http://www.gwu.edu/~spiders/content/publications/Hormiga%202002.pdf|url-status= live}}</ref>
* 2003: A [[Orson Welles (crater)|crater on Mars]] was named in his honor.<ref>{{gpn|4499}}</ref>
* 2007: A statue of Welles sculpted by Oja Kodar was installed in the city of [[Split, Croatia]].<ref name="Feder" />{{Rp|256}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2008/01/17/feature-03 |title=Orson Welles becomes 'Citizen of Split' |author=Ivo Scepanovic |publisher=SETimes |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006095136/http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2008/01/17/feature-03 |date=January 17, 2008 |archive-date=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>
* 2013: On February 10, 2013, the [[Woodstock Opera House]] in Woodstock, Illinois, dedicated its stage to Welles, honoring the site of his American debut as a professional theatre director.<ref name="Dedication">{{cite web |url=http://www.wellesnet.com/?p=4677 |title=Orson Welles Stage dedicated at Woodstock Opera House |publisher=Wellesnet |date=February 10, 2013 |access-date=September 23, 2014 |archive-date=December 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205164510/https://www.wellesnet.com/orson-welles-stage-dedicated-at-woodstock-opera-house/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
*2015: Throughout 2015, numerous festivals and events observed the 100th anniversary of Welles's birth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellesnet.com/orson-welles-celebrations-in-woodstock-illinois/ |title=Orson Welles centenary celebrations and film festivals |publisher=Wellesnet |access-date=May 7, 2015 |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528063345/http://www.wellesnet.com/orson-welles-celebrations-in-woodstock-illinois/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* 2017: A survey of critical consensus, best-of lists, and historical retrospectives finds Welles to be the second most acclaimed director of all time (behind [[Alfred Hitchcock]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |title=The 1,000 Greatest Films (Top 250 Directors) |last=Georgaris |first=Bill |date=February 2017 |website=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They? |access-date=April 27, 2017 |archive-date=August 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812074314/http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Cultural references ==
<!-- Listing trivial mentions adds no value to the encyclopedic treatment of this subject. Before adding items to this section, please read [[MOS:POPCULT]]. Additions that appear to be insignificant and/or are not attributed to a reliable source WILL be removed. If an item you have added has been removed and you wish to contest its removal, please start a discussion on this article's talk page proposing that it be restored. -->
* Director [[Peter Jackson]] cast Montreal actor Jean Guérin as Welles in his 1994 film, ''[[Heavenly Creatures]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brownstein |first=Bill |date=April 19, 1993 |title=Film buff to star as his hero; Montreal lookalike gets Orson Welles role in N.Z. |newspaper=Montreal Gazette }}</ref>
* [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] portrayed Welles in a cameo appearance in [[Tim Burton]]'s 1994 film, ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]],'' where he briefly appears and encourages [[Edward D. Wood|the eponymous filmmaker]] to fight for making his movies his own way in spite of his producers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/ed-wood-1994 |title=Ed Wood |last=Ebert |first=Roger |date=October 7, 1994 |website=RogerEbert.com |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510052709/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/ed-wood-1994 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* Voice actor [[Maurice LaMarche]] is known for his Welles impression, heard in ''Ed Wood'' (in which he dubbed the dialog of Vincent D'Onofrio); the 1994–95 primetime animated series, ''[[The Critic]]''; a 2006 [[Treehouse of Horror XVII|episode]] of ''[[The Simpsons]]''; and a 2011 [[Lrrreconcilable Ndndifferences|episode]] of ''[[Futurama]]'' for which LaMarche won an [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Emmy Award]]. The voice he created for the character Brain from the animated series ''[[Animaniacs]]'' and ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]'' was largely influenced by Welles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/ubiquitous-voice-actor-maurice-lamarche-on-ifutura-81523 |title=Ubiquitous voice actor Maurice LaMarche on Futurama, Pinky and The Brain, and more |last=Robinson |first=Tasha |date=June 20, 2012 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=June 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630234558/http://www.avclub.com/article/ubiquitous-voice-actor-maurice-lamarche-on-ifutura-81523 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* The 1996 film ''[[The Battle Over Citizen Kane]]'', which chronicles the conflict between Welles and Hearst, was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sauter|first=Michael|date=November 17, 2000|title=THE BATTLE OVER CITIZEN KANE|journal=Entertainment Weekly|volume=569|via=Academic Search Complete}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|title=The 68th Academy Awards {{!}} 1996|work=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|access-date=January 15, 2018|language=en|archive-date=June 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602003028/https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1996|url-status=live}}</ref>
* Welles is a recurring character in the [[Anno Dracula series|''Anno Dracula'' series]] by author and critic [[Kim Newman]], appearing in ''[[Dracula Cha Cha Cha]]'' (1998) and ''Johnny Alucard'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://johnnyalucard.com/fiction/by-kim-newman/anno-dracula-series/ |title=Anno Dracula series |date=May 25, 2011 |website=The Kim Newman Web Site |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=September 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906044641/http://johnnyalucard.com/fiction/by-kim-newman/anno-dracula-series/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Newman |first=Kim |date=2013 |title=Anno Dracula 1976–1991: Johnny Alucard |url=http://johnnyalucard.com/fiction/by-kim-newman/anno-dracula-series/ |location=London |publisher=Titan Books |isbn=978-0-85768-536-0 |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=September 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906044641/http://johnnyalucard.com/fiction/by-kim-newman/anno-dracula-series/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In 1999 Welles appeared on a U.S. postage stamp in a scene from ''Citizen Kane''. The [[United States Postal Service]] was petitioned to honor Welles with a stamp in 2015, the 100th anniversary of his birth, but the effort did not succeed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellesnet.com/charlton-heston-ingrid-bergman-and-elizabeth-taylor-poised-to-be-honored-on-u-s-postage-stamps-but-not-orson-welles/ |title=Charlton Heston, Ingrid Bergman and Elizabeth Taylor poised to be honored on U.S. postage stamps, but not Orson Welles |last=Kelly |first=Ray |date=February 25, 2014 |publisher=Wellesnet |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=September 26, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926023713/http://www.wellesnet.com/charlton-heston-ingrid-bergman-and-elizabeth-taylor-poised-to-be-honored-on-u-s-postage-stamps-but-not-orson-welles/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* The 1999 [[HBO]] docudrama, ''[[RKO 281]]'', tells the story of the making of ''Citizen Kane'', starring [[Liev Schreiber]] as Orson Welles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ross|first1=Benjamin|title=RKO 281|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120801/?ref_=nv_sr_6|website=IMDB|access-date=February 6, 2018|date=November 20, 1999|archive-date=December 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205164442/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120801/?ref_=nv_sr_6|url-status=live}}</ref>
* Tim Robbins's 1999 film ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]'' chronicles the process and events surrounding Welles and John Houseman's production of the 1937 musical by Marc Blitzstein. Welles is played by actor [[Angus MacFadyen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cradle Will Rock (1999)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0150216/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|website=IMDB|access-date=February 6, 2018|archive-date=December 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205164442/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0150216/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|url-status=live}}</ref>
* [[Austin Pendleton]]'s 2000 play, ''[[Orson's Shadow]]'', concerns the 1960 London production of [[Eugène Ionesco]]'s play ''[[Rhinoceros (play)|Rhinoceros]]'' directed by Welles and starring [[Laurence Olivier]]. First presented by the [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company]] in 2000, the play opened off-Broadway in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/alls-welles-pendletons-orsons-shadow-opens-off-broadway-march-13-124650 |title=All's Welles: Pendleton's Orson's Shadow Opens Off-Broadway March 13 |author-link1=Robert Simonson |last=Simonson |first=Robert |date=March 13, 2005 |website=Playbill |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924191241/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/alls-welles-pendletons-orsons-shadow-opens-off-broadway-march-13-124650 |url-status=live }}</ref> and had its European premiere in London in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://southwarkplayhouse.co.uk/archives/orsons-shadow/ |title=Orson's Shadow |publisher=[[Southwark Playhouse]] |access-date=August 27, 2015 |date=July 2015 |archive-date=September 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912140618/http://southwarkplayhouse.co.uk/archives/orsons-shadow/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* In [[Michael Chabon]]'s 2000 [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction|Pulitzer Prize]]-winning novel ''[[The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier & Clay]]'', the protagonists meet Orson Welles and attend the premiere of ''Citizen Kane''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Yanofsky |first=Joel |author-link=Joel Yanofsky |date=December 9, 2000 |title=Escapist fiction: Old-fashioned storytelling with a Houdini-like hero  |newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]  }}</ref>
* In the film ''[[Fade to Black (2006 film)|Fade to Black]]'' (2006), a fictional thriller set during Welles's 1948 journey to Rome to star in the movie ''[[Black Magic (1949 film)|Black Magic]]'', [[Danny Huston]] stars as Welles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Russell |first=Ken |author-link=Ken Russell |date=March 6, 2008 |title=Fade to Black gives us Orson Welles as a hungry hustler |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/article2426813.ece |newspaper=[[The Times]] |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=May 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508102554/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/article2426813.ece |url-status=live }}</ref>
* ''[[Me and Orson Welles]]'' (2009), based on [[Robert Kaplow]]'s 2003 novel,<ref>{{cite book |last=Kaplow |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Kaplow |date=2003 |title=Me and Orson Welles  |location=San Francisco |publisher=MacAdam Cage Publishing |isbn=978-1-931561-49-5 }}</ref> stars [[Zac Efron]] as a teenager who convinces Welles ([[Christian McKay]]) to cast him in his 1937 production of ''[[Caesar (Mercury Theatre)|Julius Caesar]]''. McKay received numerous accolades for his performance, including a [[BAFTA]] nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/film-awards-nominations-announced|title=Film Awards Nominations Announced|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=February 2, 2018|date=January 21, 2010|archive-date=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203064740/http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/film-awards-nominations-announced|url-status=live}}</ref>
* Welles is the central character in "Ian, George, and George," a novelette by [[Paul Levinson]] published in 2013 in ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1643549|title=Ian, George, and George|publisher=Internet Speculative Fiction Database|access-date=January 19, 2016|archive-date=April 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406132058/http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1643549|url-status=live}}</ref>
* In 2014 comedic actor [[Jack Black]] portrayed Welles in the sketch comedy show ''[[Drunk History]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellesnet.com/video-jack-black-and-drunk-history-making-citizen-kane/ |title=Video: Jack Black and 'Drunk History – Making Citizen Kane' |date=August 9, 2014 |publisher=Wellesnet |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=July 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710045905/http://www.wellesnet.com/video-jack-black-and-drunk-history-making-citizen-kane/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
* A 2014 documentary by [[Chuck Workman]], ''[[Magician: The Astonishing Life and Work of Orson Welles]]'', was released to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cohenmedia.net/films/magician |title=Magician: The Astonishing Life & Work of Orson Welles |publisher=Cohen Media Group |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071452/http://cohenmedia.net/films/magician |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/magician-astonishing-life-work-orson-733675 |title='Magician: The Astonishing Life and Work of Orson Welles': Telluride Review |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |date=September 16, 2014 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=August 27, 2015 |archive-date=August 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809120633/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/magician-astonishing-life-work-orson-733675 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* Rapper [[Logic (rapper)|Logic]] samples Orson Welles twice on his 2020 album No Pressure, with a portion of the August 11, 1946 "Orson Welles Commentaries" episode featured as the outro to the album, titled Obediently Yours.
* [[Tom Burke (actor)|Tom Burke]] portrayed Welles in [[David Fincher]]'s 2020 film, ''[[Mank]]'', which focuses on [[Herman J. Mankiewicz]], the co-writer of ''[[Citizen Kane]]''.
* Welles is portrayed by three avatars as he comes to grips with his own death in the 2020 filmopera ''Orson Rehearsed''<ref>[http://www.orsonrehearsed.art Orson Rehearsed Website] Retrieved February 11, 20201.</ref> by composer director [[Daron Hagen]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hagen|first1=Daron|title=Orson Rehearsed|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt13204902/|website=IMDB|access-date=February 11, 2021|date=February 2, 2021|archive-date=December 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

